@include ../parser.ts.hint

# module keywords

The templates directory is the extensibility layer between the parser and the compiler. Each .ts.hint file here is a rendering contract for one directive type: it tells the compiler exactly how to transform a {RawBlock} into the markdown section that appears in the final prompt payload.

The compiler never hard-codes directive semantics. For each block in {ParseResult}.blocks it loads the template whose filename matches the block's directive field, binds the block's data into a {TemplateContext}, and writes the rendered section to the output buffer. Adding support for a new directive requires one new .ts.hint file in this directory — zero changes to the compiler core.

# entity TemplateContext

The variables the compiler binds from a {RawBlock} before executing any template.

- directive: {Directive}
  which block type is being rendered — always matches the template filename stem
- name: string | undefined
  the optional identifier attached to this block (entity name, function name, etc.)
- body: string
  the block's full text content after all {single-brace} cross-references have been resolved
- reads: Map<string, {ReadRef}>
  every `# read` intent across all files, keyed by reference name — used for {variable} cross-reference resolution in other blocks

# entity ReadBlockContext

The extra field the compiler makes available when rendering a `# read` block specifically. The `# read` header has a non-standard syntax (`# read {glob} as [name]`) so the compiler parses the glob out of the `{glob}` portion (before `as`) separately from the name and body.

- name: string — the reference identifier (e.g. 'AppLogger')
- glob: string — the file path or glob pattern from the `{glob}` portion of the header (before the `as` keyword)
- body: string — the description lines the developer wrote beneath the directive

# entity TemplateOutput

What the compiler collects from each rendered template and assembles into the final prompt payload.

- section: string
  the fully rendered markdown string to append to the output buffer
- directive: {Directive}
  preserved for ordering, deduplication, and section grouping logic

# action renderPrompt

The full compiler rendering lifecycle — produces the complete final prompt from a {ParseResult}:

1. Render header.ts.hint and write it to the output buffer first.
2. Iterate over {ParseResult}.blocks in order. `# read` blocks render first (they appear before other directives in the cascade), but the compiler processes them in the same loop — no separate pass.
3. For each block, execute {renderBlock}.
4. Render footer.ts.hint and append it to the output buffer last.
5. Join the buffer and emit to stdout or the designated output file.

# action renderBlock

The compiler executes this for every {RawBlock} in the flat ordered blocks list:

1. If block.directive is 'notes', drop it silently — never load a template for it.
2. Resolve the template path: keywords/{block.directive}.ts.hint
3. If the file does not exist, throw AppError(PARSE_ERROR) naming the unknown directive.
4. Bind a {TemplateContext} from the block's directive, name, and body.
5. For `# read` blocks additionally bind the glob parsed from the header line as a {ReadBlockContext}.
6. Resolve all {single-brace} variable tokens in body against the reads map before binding.
7. Extract the Output specification from the template and fill all {{double-brace}} interpolation tokens.
8. Append the resulting {TemplateOutput}.section to the prompt buffer.

# rule

- Every value in the {Directive} union must have a corresponding .ts.hint file in this directory. The complete set is: read, lang, deps, build, module, app, lib, res, require, entity, function, ui, action, rule, good, bad, example, test, notes. An unmatched directive at compile time is an immediate PARSE_ERROR.
- Template files follow the naming convention {directive}.ts.hint. The header and footer use the reserved names header.ts.hint and footer.ts.hint.
- Template files are valid HINT files — they self-document their own rendering contracts and can be processed by the HINT toolchain.
- {{double-brace}} tokens mark compiler interpolation points. They are distinct from HINT's {single-brace} cross-references, which the compiler resolves before any template executes.
- {{#name}}...{{/name}} is a conditional block — the compiler includes its content only when the name field is non-empty.
- Templates describe intent and output shape only. No logic or conditional branching lives in the template file — the compiler implements those from the rules each template declares.
- Directive keywords are case-insensitive and accept full-word aliases. The compiler normalizes all forms to the canonical keyword before blocks reach the templates — `# language` becomes `lang`, `# dependencies` becomes `deps`, `# application` becomes `app`, `# library` becomes `lib`, `# interface` becomes `ui`, `# resource` becomes `res`, `## argument` becomes `arg`, `## returns` becomes `return`. Templates only ever see the canonical form.
